From Clinton HQ The White House Subject CLINTON President's Remarks in Photo Op with Vaclav Havel THE WHITE HOUSE Office of the Press Secretary For Immediate Release April REMARKS BY THE PRESIDENT IN PHOTO OPPORTUNITY WITH VACLAV HAVEL The Oval Office EDT Q President President Havel is here for the Holocaust Museum opening and you toured the museum last All this focus on the Holocaust how does that weigh on your decision making process as far as Bosnia is concerned THE PRESIDENT Well I think the Holocaust is the most extreme example the world has ever known of ethnic And I think that even in its more limited manifestations it's an idea that should be You couldn't help thinking about That's not to compare the two They're not identical everyone knows But I think that the United States should always seek an opportunity to stand up against at least to speak out against Q Sir how close are you to a decision on more sanctions on Bosnia THE PRESIDENT Well of course we've got the Ambassador Albright was instrumental in the vote to strengthen the sanctions and they are quite And we now are putting our heads at the business of implementing them and looking at what other options we ought to And I don't have anything else to say except to tell you that I spent quite a bit of time on it and will continue to over the next several Q Following your meeting today sir are you any closer to some sort of military presence there THE PRESIDENT I have not made any Q President Clinton why have you decided to meet with Havel THE PRESIDENT Well I'm just honored that he would come and see I'm glad he's here in the United States for the dedication of the Holocaust He is a figure widely admired in our country and around the world and a very important person in Europe and a very important person to the United So I'm hoping that we'll have a chance to talk about the new Czech republic and what kinds of things we can do together to support the causes we believe EDT